","1150":"1150","about 1177":"circa 1177","about 1175":"circa 1175","Lewes, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Lewes, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Nunney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Nunney, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Nunney Castle, Frome, Somersetshire, England":"Nunney, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Paris, Seine, Île-de-France, France":"Paris, Seine, Frankrijk","Childrey, Berkshire, England":"Childrey, Berkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1150–about 1177":"about 1150–about 1177","1150–1177":"1150–1177","1150–Male":"1150–Deceased","1150–1213":"1150–1213","1175–1239":"1175–1239","1120–1190":"1120–1190","–Female":"Deceased","about 1150":"about 1150","1190":"1190","1239":"1239","1213":"1213","1177":"1177","1154":"1154","1165":"1165","1120":"1120","1175":"1175","1150":"1150","about 1177":"about 1177","about 1175":"about 1175","Lewes, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Lewes, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Nunney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Nunney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Nunney Castle, Frome, Somersetshire, England":"Nunney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Paris, Seine, Île-de-France, France":"Paris, Seine, France","Childrey, Berkshire, England":"Childrey, Berkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mare","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Americo, Cesareo, Fernando, Ines, Javier, Jose, Marcos.  Portuguese Henrique.  Italian Antonio, Gino, Olindo, Silvio, Vito.  Dutch Andries.","Italian: topographic name for someone living by the sea, from <i>mare</i> ‘sea’.","English: variant of   Mear  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Marucci","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Antonio, Silvio, Angelo, Carmela, Domenic, Donato, Egidio, Guido, Licinio, Lorenzo, Luciano.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Maruccio</i>, a pet form of   Mare   or   Mari  ."]},{"name":"Marelli","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Giuseppe, Angelo, Dante.","Italian:","patronymic or plural form of a diminutive of   Mare  ."]},{"name":"Mear","meanings":["English: variant of   Mear  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish: from <b>Ó Meidhir</b> ‘descendant of <i>Meidhir</i>’, a personal name based on <i>meidhir</i> ‘mirth’. Compare   Myers  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]},{"name":"la","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Orchid’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de la Mare was born about 1150, in Nunney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Sir Thomas de la Mare and Unknown. She had at least 1 son with Sir Simone Sidney. She died about 1177, in Paris, Seine, France, at the age of 29."},"et":{"about 1150–about 1177":"umbes 1150–umbes 1177","1150–1177":"1150–1177","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1150–1213":"1150–1213","1175–1239":"1175–1239","1120–1190":"1120–1190","–Female":"Surnud","about 1150":"umbes 1150","1190":"1190","1239":"1239","1213":"1213","1177":"1177","1154":"1154","1165":"1165","1120":"1120","1175":"1175","1150":"1150","about 1177":"umbes 1177","about 1175":"umbes 1175","Lewes, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Lewes, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Nunney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Nunney, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Nunney Castle, Frome, Somersetshire, England":"Nunney, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Paris, Seine, Île-de-France, France":"Paris, Seine, Prantsusmaa","Childrey, Berkshire, England":"Childrey, Berkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1150–about 1177":"noin 1150–noin 1177","1150–1177":"1150–1177","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1150–1213":"1150–1213","1175–1239":"1175–1239","1120–1190":"1120–1190","–Female":"Kuollut","about 1150":"noin 1150","1190":"1190","1239":"1239","1213":"1213","1177":"1177","1154":"1154","1165":"1165","1120":"1120","1175":"1175","1150":"1150","about 1177":"noin 1177","about 1175":"noin 1175","Lewes, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Lewes, Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Nunney, 